<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/rights-groups-50-killed-sudan-protests-062602374.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/bthEnRZvKr6Ff27gEgkaWQ--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3B4b2ZmPTUwO3B5b2ZmPTA7cT04NTt3PTEzMA--/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/a3917ef17b297f203e0f6a706700c98a.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="Sudanese boys walk amid burned vehicles after rioters torched a fuel station in Khartoum, Sudan, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. Sudanese authorities have deployed troops around vital installations and gas stations in Khartoum following days of deadly rioting over gas price hikes. (AP Photo/Abd Raouf)" align="left" title="Sudanese boys walk amid burned vehicles after rioters torched a fuel station in Khartoum, Sudan, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. Sudanese authorities have deployed troops around vital installations and gas stations in Khartoum following days of deadly rioting over gas price hikes. (AP Photo/Abd Raouf)" border="0" /></a>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) — Two leading rights groups say Sudanese police killed at least 50 people this week, often &quot;shooting to kill&quot; when they moved to quell angry protests over the government&#039;s cut of fuel subsidies.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/icelands-wild-scenery-tax-breaks-lure-hollywood-060820017--finance.html' target="_blank">Iceland's wild scenery, tax breaks lure Hollywood</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/icelands-wild-scenery-tax-breaks-lure-hollywood-060820017--finance.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/H8q8BoQsW79d_HVKejXuvA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/2482896c97d38d203e0f6a706700dd64.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="In this photo provided by Truenorth Productions, US actor Clint Eastwood, centre, and crew members film on location for the 2006 film Flags of our Fathers, in the Reykjanes Peninsula, Iceland. Iceland is turning to Hollywood for much needed revenue and jobs, as well as a touch of glamour, as it struggles to recover from a nationwide banking and currency collapse. This remote North Atlantic island’s vast and unforgiving landscape has served as a stand-in for other planets, the Himalayas and even HBO’s Game of Thrones’ snow-filled fantasy world in recent productions. The country’s unique environment, along with generous tax incentives, continues to attract some of the biggest Hollywood filmmakers and television producers. (AP Photo/Truenorth Productions)" align="left" title="In this photo provided by Truenorth Productions, US actor Clint Eastwood, centre, and crew members film on location for the 2006 film Flags of our Fathers, in the Reykjanes Peninsula, Iceland. Iceland is turning to Hollywood for much needed revenue and jobs, as well as a touch of glamour, as it struggles to recover from a nationwide banking and currency collapse. This remote North Atlantic island’s vast and unforgiving landscape has served as a stand-in for other planets, the Himalayas and even HBO’s Game of Thrones’ snow-filled fantasy world in recent productions. The country’s unique environment, along with generous tax incentives, continues to attract some of the biggest Hollywood filmmakers and television producers. (AP Photo/Truenorth Productions)" border="0" /></a>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) — It has doubled as an alien planet, a Himalayan peak and even the snow-filled fantasy world of the Game of Thrones. Still recovering from financial collapse, Iceland can perhaps be forgiven for seeking alternate identities.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/london-police-super-recognizers-fight-crime-060427815.html' target="_blank">London police use super recognizers to fight crime</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/london-police-super-recognizers-fight-crime-060427815.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/ZPxNrBhO3D87x0DXYNToBA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/f327c7ce794576203e0f6a706700e1bf.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="In this photo taken on Wednesday, Sept. 18, 2013, DCI Mick Neville who oversees the Metropolitan Police Circulation Unit poses for photographs in his office at the force&#039;s New Scotland Yard headquarters in London. The study of facial recognition is in its infancy. But since 2011, about 200 London police officers have been recruited to an elite squad of super recognizers. Officials say they have tripled the number of criminal suspects identified from surveillance photos or on the street each week, and even helped prevent some crimes like muggings, drug deals or assaults. (AP Photo/Matt Dunham)" align="left" title="In this photo taken on Wednesday, Sept. 18, 2013, DCI Mick Neville who oversees the Metropolitan Police Circulation Unit poses for photographs in his office at the force&#039;s New Scotland Yard headquarters in London. The study of facial recognition is in its infancy. But since 2011, about 200 London police officers have been recruited to an elite squad of super recognizers. Officials say they have tripled the number of criminal suspects identified from surveillance photos or on the street each week, and even helped prevent some crimes like muggings, drug deals or assaults. (AP Photo/Matt Dunham)" border="0" /></a>LONDON (AP) — Paul Hyland almost never forgets a face. He&#039;s a &quot;super recognizer,&quot; and that&#039;s giving an unusual kind of help to his employer: Scotland Yard.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/confusion-over-maldives-election-officials-clash-060402559.html' target="_blank">Confusion over Maldives election as officials clash</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/confusion-over-maldives-election-officials-clash-060402559.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/zd1Gob8UY5xpqNiZepn6sA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/afp.com/55432519de3497493afb5d6aaa6d2e351cd50990.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="Protestors gather outside the court that suspended the September 28 run-off presidential elections in Male on September 26, 2013" align="left" title="Protestors gather outside the court that suspended the September 28 run-off presidential elections in Male on September 26, 2013" border="0" /></a>Colombo (Sri Lanka) (AFP) - The Maldives&#039; Election Commission sparked confusion on Friday over whether elections originally scheduled for this weekend but suspended by the Supreme Court would go ahead on the troubled Indian Ocean archipelago.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/us-allies-see-chance-resolve-iran-nuke-impasse-054716013.html' target="_blank">US, allies see chance to resolve Iran nuke impasse</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/us-allies-see-chance-resolve-iran-nuke-impasse-054716013.html"><img src="http://l1.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/5bVjwDy8vwc1d2bI4UFshA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/cf858b147ca586203e0f6a706700fbe5.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="CORRECTS DATE TO THURSDAY, SEPT. 26, 2013 FROM WEDNESDAY - U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry, left, and Iranian Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Zarif attend a meeting of the five permanent members of the Security Council plus Germany during the 68th session of the United Nations General Assembly at U.N. headquarters, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. (AP Photo/Jason DeCrow)" align="left" title="CORRECTS DATE TO THURSDAY, SEPT. 26, 2013 FROM WEDNESDAY - U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry, left, and Iranian Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Zarif attend a meeting of the five permanent members of the Security Council plus Germany during the 68th session of the United Nations General Assembly at U.N. headquarters, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. (AP Photo/Jason DeCrow)" border="0" /></a>UNITED NATIONS (AP) — The U.S. and its international partners emerged from a meeting with Iran declaring that a &quot;window of opportunity has opened&quot; to peacefully settle their nuclear standoff. But diplomats asked Tehran to come back with a detailed plan of action to reassure the world it is not trying to build an atomic bomb.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/japan-defence-chief-bolster-surveillance-over-pacific-054203963.html' target="_blank">Japan Defence chief: Need to bolster surveillance over Pacific</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/japan-defence-chief-bolster-surveillance-over-pacific-054203963.html"><img src="http://l.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/v9BJS0Yq3nRBKc0f.TEA7w--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2013-09-27T054203Z_1_CBRE98Q0FU600_RTROPTP_2_JAPAN.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="Japan&#039;s Defence Minister Onodera attends a news conference at the Japan National Press Club in Tokyo" align="left" title="Japan&#039;s Defence Minister Onodera attends a news conference at the Japan National Press Club in Tokyo" border="0" /></a>TOKYO (Reuters) - Japanese Defence Minister Itsunori Onodera said on Friday that Japan needs to expand its surveillance activities to cover the Pacific Ocean, as well as the Sea of Japan and the East China Sea, to better protect to its maritime interests. Tokyo is locked in a bitter territorial dispute with Beijing over tiny a group of East China Sea islets, called the Senkaku in Japan and Diaoyu in China. &quot;So far, we have been conducting routine surveillance activities in such areas as the Sea of Japan and the East China Sea. </p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/un-council-closes-syria-resolution-diplomats-210825994.html' target="_blank">US, Russia break deadlock on Syria chemical arms</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/un-council-closes-syria-resolution-diplomats-210825994.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/n6dD8vu4Cho4HvOdnHqhjw--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/afp.com/c61b40a1bd185ce723478b193d08d18568231e79.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="US State Secretary John Kerry (L) and Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov talk at the UN General Assembly in New York, September 24, 2013" align="left" title="US State Secretary John Kerry (L) and Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov talk at the UN General Assembly in New York, September 24, 2013" border="0" /></a>UNITED NATIONS (United States) (AFP) - The United States and Russia agreed a draft UN Security Council resolution on destroying Syria&#039;s chemical weapons, breaking a prolonged deadlock over the country&#039;s conflict.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/russian-court-order-activists-held-over-arctic-oil-044631467--finance.html' target="_blank">Russian court order activists held over Arctic oil protest</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/russian-court-order-activists-held-over-arctic-oil-044631467--finance.html"><img src="http://l1.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/eG17zdx4Ydv8mqZDB9DllQ--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2013-09-27T044631Z_2_CBRE98P0T6M00_RTROPTP_2_RUSSIA-GREENPEACE.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="Handout shows a Greenpeace International activist from Canada, arrested for staging a protest at Russia&#039;s first Arctic offshore oil platform, arriving at the Leninsky District Court in Murmansk" align="left" title="Handout shows a Greenpeace International activist from Canada, arrested for staging a protest at Russia&#039;s first Arctic offshore oil platform, arriving at the Leninsky District Court in Murmansk" border="0" /></a>By Steve Gutterman MOSCOW (Reuters) - A Russian court ordered 20 Greenpeace activists from around the world to be held in custody for two months pending further investigation over a protest against offshore oil drilling in the Arctic, drawing condemnation and a vow to appeal. In proceedings that Greenpeace said evoked Soviet-era scare tactics, activists from a ship used in the protest at an oil rig were led to court in the port of Murmansk in handcuffs and held in cages for a series of hearings that ended early on Friday. </p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/russia-gay-law-creator-calls-stephen-fry-evil-042448202--oly.html' target="_blank">Russia gay law creator calls Stephen Fry evil</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/russia-gay-law-creator-calls-stephen-fry-evil-042448202--oly.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/ZEtvxViz9aSSNCiOosBTQw--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/afp.com/8ed15843de478a78aaa00af9e9811a7fe7f423c0.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="British actor Stephen Fry (R) speaks with Russian lawmaker Vitaly Milonov (L) in Saint Petersburg, on March 14, 2013" align="left" title="British actor Stephen Fry (R) speaks with Russian lawmaker Vitaly Milonov (L) in Saint Petersburg, on March 14, 2013" border="0" /></a>Moscow (AFP) - Vitaly Milonov believes that British actor Stephen Fry is a âbringer of evilâ, thinks homosexuality is a perversion and thanks God for giving Russia Vladimir Putin to defend its values.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/brazil-family-fights-keep-house-trained-tigers-040547406.html' target="_blank">Brazil family fights to keep house-trained tigers</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/brazil-family-fights-keep-house-trained-tigers-040547406.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/friyJnIPk48au4MdZqAl3Q--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/c181b1bc97a38c203e0f6a70670047ea.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="Ary Borges feeds his tiger named Dan at his home in Maringa, Brazil, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. Borges is in a legal battle with federal wildlife officials to keep his endangered animals from undergoing vasectomies and being taken away from him. He defends his right to breed the animals and says he gives them a better home than they might find elsewhere in Brazil. (AP Photo/Renata Brito)" align="left" title="Ary Borges feeds his tiger named Dan at his home in Maringa, Brazil, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. Borges is in a legal battle with federal wildlife officials to keep his endangered animals from undergoing vasectomies and being taken away from him. He defends his right to breed the animals and says he gives them a better home than they might find elsewhere in Brazil. (AP Photo/Renata Brito)" border="0" /></a>MARINGA, Brazil (AP) — Dan slurped desperately on his pink nursing bottle and spilled milk all over the place, while his brother Tom patiently waited to take a swim in the family pool.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/dominican-court-ends-citizenship-residents-041119912.html' target="_blank">Dominican court ends citizenship of some residents</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/dominican-court-ends-citizenship-residents-041119912.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/r9nYoD7YjYmj3VUgqXTF4A--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/0759a4e096bf88203e0f6a706700b572.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="FILE - In this Aug. 12, 2013 file photo, a youth of Haitian descent holds a sign that reads in Spanish &quot;I&#039;m Dominican&quot; during a protest demanding that President Danilo Medina stop the process to invalidate their birth certificates after authorities retained their ID cards, in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic. The Dominican Republic&#039;s top court on Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013 stripped citizenship from thousands of people born to migrants who came illegally, a category that overwhelmingly includes Haitians brought in to work on farms. The decision cannot be appealed, and it affects all those born since 1929. (AP Photo/Ezequiel Abiu Lopez, File)" align="left" title="FILE - In this Aug. 12, 2013 file photo, a youth of Haitian descent holds a sign that reads in Spanish &quot;I&#039;m Dominican&quot; during a protest demanding that President Danilo Medina stop the process to invalidate their birth certificates after authorities retained their ID cards, in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic. The Dominican Republic&#039;s top court on Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013 stripped citizenship from thousands of people born to migrants who came illegally, a category that overwhelmingly includes Haitians brought in to work on farms. The decision cannot be appealed, and it affects all those born since 1929. (AP Photo/Ezequiel Abiu Lopez, File)" border="0" /></a>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) — Thousands of Dominican Republic residents have been thrown into limbo by a ruling from the country&#039;s highest court that strips citizenship from anyone born to migrants who entered illegally. The decree affects mainly people of Haitian descent and is likely to worsen already acrimonious relations with neighboring Haiti.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/deal-reached-un-resolution-syria-weapons-221308298.html' target="_blank">Deal reached on UN resolution on Syria weapons</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/deal-reached-un-resolution-syria-weapons-221308298.html"><img src="http://l.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/RqRk0QEVSnkXzyb9j_HGuw--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/6f16492a7cd487203e0f6a7067005c5d.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="President of the Opposition Syrian Coalition, Ahmad Jarba, left, French Foreign Minister Laurent Fabius, center, and American Secretary of State John Kerry attend a Ministerial Meeting of the Group of Friends of the Syrian people, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013 at United Nations headquarters. (AP Photo/Mary Altaffer)" align="left" title="President of the Opposition Syrian Coalition, Ahmad Jarba, left, French Foreign Minister Laurent Fabius, center, and American Secretary of State John Kerry attend a Ministerial Meeting of the Group of Friends of the Syrian people, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013 at United Nations headquarters. (AP Photo/Mary Altaffer)" border="0" /></a>UNITED NATIONS (AP) — The five permanent members of the deeply divided U.N. Security Council reached agreement Thursday on a resolution to eliminate Syria&#039;s chemical weapons, a major step in taking the most controversial weapon off the battlefield of the world&#039;s deadliest ongoing conflict.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/talks-landmark-climate-report-wrapping-040414109.html' target="_blank">Talks on landmark climate report wrapping up</a><br />
STOCKHOLM (AP) — Participants of an international conference on climate science say delegates have finished talks on a landmark report on global warming and are ready to formally adopt the document.
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/kerrys-talk-prompts-rare-private-meeting-between-iran-035332741.html' target="_blank">Kerry's 'Shall we talk?' prompts rare private meeting between Iran and U.S.</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/kerrys-talk-prompts-rare-private-meeting-between-iran-035332741.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/5CA35bLUZppbI2.LD97pLA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2013-09-27T035332Z_1_CBRE98Q0ATC00_RTROPTP_2_UN-ASSEMBLY.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry and Iranian Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Zarif are seated during a meeting at the UN Headquarters in New York" align="left" title="U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry and Iranian Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Zarif are seated during a meeting at the UN Headquarters in New York" border="0" /></a>By Lesley Wroughton UNITED NATIONS (Reuters) - First there was a handshake, then an invitation to talk and finally a 30-minute tete-a-tete that made for the highest-level official meeting between the United States and Iran in more than three decades. The opportunity for a rare meeting between U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry and his Iranian counterpart, Mohammad Javad Zarif, came after talks concluded between Zarif and foreign ministers from the six major powers on resolving Tehran&#039;s disputed nuclear program. At the start of the talks, Kerry and Zarif shook hands, a senior U.S. </p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/canadian-throws-money-ego-austrian-election-035144109.html' target="_blank">Canadian throws money, ego into Austrian election</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/canadian-throws-money-ego-austrian-election-035144109.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/Xns7ahLfCRg3G7Z99z9cxg--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/afp.com/9fe585553fcd2e511a0a392a8fd5503b744da3b1.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="AUSTRIA-POLITICS-VOTE-STRONACH" align="left" title="AUSTRIA-POLITICS-VOTE-STRONACH" border="0" /></a>Eisenstadt (Austria) (AFP) - On a cool day in Eisenstadt, far from the prairies of Canada where he made his fortune, billionaire Frank Stronach rails against corrupt politicians, posing as the prodigal son who has returned to save Austria.</p><br clear="all"/>
